The Japanese economy is an industrialized, free-market economy. It ranks fourth in the world in GDP -  after the U.S., China, and India - in terms of international purchasing power parity. With cooperation between government and industry, a strong work ethic, mastery of industrial technology, and a small defense outlay (1% of GDP compared to 4.7% of GDP of the US defense expenditure budget), Japan has managed to become the second most technologically-powerful economy in the world. 
\fs24 \

\fs32 Japan has experienced spectacular growth in the past. In the 1960s, it had an average of 10% 10 annual real GDP growth. However, its growth rate fell to an average of 5% in the 1970s and further to 4% in the 1980s. Over-investment and speculative excesses from stock and real estate markets created a "bubble economy" which finally burst in a stock market crash in 1989. Growth slowed dramatically in the 1990s averaging just 1.7%. During this period, Japan experienced a prolonged period of deflation. The government's efforts to revive economic growth in recent years have been met with little success, partly because of the recession in the U.S., Europe, and other Asian countries. Since 2004, though, the economy has begun to improve and calm the fears of deflation in prices and slow growth of economic activity. 
\fs24 \

\fs32 Japan experienced periodic negative growth to its GDP in the past decade and in 1993-95, 1997- 1999, and 2001-02, the Japanese economy had actual contraction. Since 1998, it has experienced a prolonged period of deflation, where its nominal GDP growth rate has been lower than its real growth rate.
